    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Why Business English Is Different from Regular English</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">General English classes teach you to communicate in daily situations. Ordering food, making friends, traveling. These are useful skills, but they will not help you close a major deal or lead a meeting with international clients.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Business English is a specialized skill set. It includes vocabulary for negotiations, emails, presentations, and conference calls. It also covers cultural communication styles, formal register, and the ability to explain complex ideas clearly under pressure.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">A good business English tutor understands that you are not learning English from scratch. You are learning to use English as a professional tool. The best tutors adapt their lessons to your industry, your job level, and your specific communication challenges.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">What to Look for in a Business English Tutor</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Not every tutor who claims to teach business English actually understands what that means. Here are the key qualities to search for when you start your search.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Industry Experience</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The best business tutors have worked in corporate environments or studied business communication formally. They understand terms like ROI, cash flow, deliverables, and stakeholder management. They can teach you the vocabulary and phrases that actually appear in your work.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Flexible Scheduling</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Business professionals do not have fixed schedules. You might need lessons at 7am before the office opens, or at 9pm after international calls. Look for tutors who offer booking systems that match your calendar, not the other way around.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Focus on Real Communication</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The most valuable business English practice happens through real conversations. Role-play meetings, rehearse presentations, draft emails together. Avoid tutors who spend most of the lesson on grammar drills. You need speaking practice that mimics your actual work situations.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Feedback on Your Specific Weaknesses</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">A professional tutor identifies where you lose clarity or confidence. Maybe you freeze during Q&A sessions. Maybe your written emails sound too casual. Maybe you struggle with accented colleagues on calls. Good tutors diagnose these problems and build targeted practice around them.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Top English Tutors for Business Professionals</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Here are the platforms and tutor types that work best for career-focused English learners.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">See Guru: Best Overall for Business Professionals</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">See Guru connects you with freelance tutors from around the world, many of whom specialize in business and corporate English. The platform gives you direct access to teacher profiles, reviews, and pricing so you can find the right match fast.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">What makes See Guru particularly strong for business professionals is the marketplace model. Tutors set their own schedules, which means you can book early morning or late evening slots without fighting for limited availability. Prices start at $5 per hour for certified teachers, with professional business tutors typically charging between $15 and $40 per hour depending on experience and credentials.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">You can filter tutors by specialty, including business English, conversation practice, interview preparation, and presentation skills. Many tutors on See Guru have backgrounds in corporate training, international business, or teaching English to professionals specifically.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">iTalki: Large Pool of Business Tutors</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">iTalki has one of the largest tutor networks in the online language learning space. You will find plenty of options for business English, from casual conversation practice to intensive corporate training programs.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The platform offers professional tutors with verified credentials and community tutors with more affordable rates. Business lessons typically run between $10 and $30 per hour. iTalki also has a structured lesson format that some learners find helpful for staying organized.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Preply: Structured Corporate Training</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Preply emphasizes academic quality and tutors go through a vetting process before they can teach on the platform. This makes it easier to find qualified business English instructors without spending hours reviewing profiles.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Pricing on Preply tends to be slightly higher, with most business tutors charging between $15 and $50 per hour. However, the platform offers corporate packages for teams, which can be useful if your company is looking to upskill multiple employees.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Cambly: Quick Access for Busy Professionals</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Cambly offers on-demand conversations with native speakers. You do not need to book in advance, which makes it convenient for last-minute practice before an important meeting or call.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The quality varies because you are matched randomly with available tutors. For ongoing structured business English training, other platforms may serve you better. But for casual speaking practice and maintaining fluency, Cambly is a solid option.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">How to Practice Business English Between Lessons</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Lessons once or twice a week are not enough if you want rapid progress. Here is how to reinforce what you learn in every session.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Listen to Business Podcasts and News</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Podcasts like The Economist, Bloomberg Businessweek, and BBC Business Daily expose you to real business vocabulary in context. Start with transcripts, then try listening without them as your comprehension improves.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Simulate Your Actual Work Situations</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Ask your tutor to help you prepare for specific upcoming events. A board presentation next month? Practice it five times. A difficult client call? Role-play it until you feel comfortable. Specific practice beats general conversation every time.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Read and Analyze Business Emails</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Request samples of professional emails from your tutor. Analyze the structure, the tone, and the specific phrases used. Then write your own emails and ask for corrections and improvements.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Record Your Calls and Review Them</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">With permission from the other party, record conference calls or presentations. Listen back and note where you lost your thread, used filler words, or missed vocabulary. Bring these recordings to your next lesson for focused feedback.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Common Business English Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Even advanced speakers make these mistakes in professional settings. Watch out for them in your own communication.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Being Too Direct or Too Vague</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Cultural expectations around directness vary widely. American business communication tends to be direct. Japanese and Korean business culture values indirectness and context. British English often uses polite softening phrases that can confuse non-native listeners. Understanding these differences prevents misunderstandings.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Using Jargon Incorrectly</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Every industry has its jargon. Using it incorrectly is worse than not using it at all. Learn the precise meaning and context of business terms before you drop them in meetings. When in doubt, explain in plain English.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Neglecting Written English</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Strong speaking skills do not automatically mean strong writing. Business emails, reports, and instant messages each have their own conventions. Practice writing regularly, and ask your tutor to review samples from your actual work communications.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">How Much Should You Budget for Business English Tutoring</h2>
